It has not happened yet and with October 1st being this soon It is nearly impossible for it to happen now.

Given the rates at which the TSA screened people mid-summer (rates above 2 million), projecting this makes it far more likely that it could reach over 2.3 million people as travel becomes less restricted and countries' traveling agencies open up.

TSA has been close to reaching 2.3 million screenings many times throughout 2022, however, it doesn't seem like they will reach it until thanksgiving, or Christmas when they will encounter the most travelers.

Although it has gotten close, it doesn't seem like the TSA will be able to reach 3 consecutive days in a row yet. However, it seems more than likely the number of passengers will surge past 2.3 million three days in a row once around the holidays, including Thanksgiving break and Christmas. November 18th to November 20th of 2022 will likely break this 2.3 million barrier, if not surge past it.

When looking at 2022 data vs 2019 data I found data that 2022 numbers haven't been increasing as a percentage of 2019 numbers for a while. This data showed that June and July are the busiest months historically which helped to guide my early thinking. I then ran a monte carlo simulation using Python and the last 3 months worth of 2022 numbers as a percentage of 2019. I then made the assumption that the 2019 to 2022 ratio is likely to be in line with the last 3 months if not increase as trips booked at the start of the year when the covid situation was less certain begin to kick in. This simulation suggested a 65% probability that the TSA will record 3 consecutive days of 2.3 or more before the 30th of July. It's also worth noting that fathers day falls on the last weekend of June in the US which will likely result in a short lived boost to numbers which have hit 2.3 on 2 consecutive days a number of times recently. Economic difficulties, continued anxiety around covid and possibly even recent gun violence in the US could work against my forecast, pushing the date of 2.3m in 3 consecutive days back into July or later. I also think there's an argument that we won't see this happen until July as major countries that fly to US airports (US, Canada, Mexico and the UK) have school summer holidays.

Lowering again on the last bin. If it doesn't happen before June 30, then it will likely happen in July. This year, July 4 is on a Monday, so when will people be flying? I'm going to guess that flights will be high July 5-8 this year. So if the question doesn't resolve in June, I think it might just resolve in the days after July 4. I think it will mostly depend on how much airlines can bring up capacity.

I analyzed the data for 2019 (before the pandemic) and set a baseline for this week (the 2nd of March). Although there are marginal increments (up to 4%) until the 2nd week of May, the increases that match the required growth rate to reach 2.3 million begin after the 3rd week of May (7% and up), and they are very consistent between the 1st and the 3rd weeks of June (10% and up). Therefore, I believe it is highly likely a 3-day row will take place by the end of May or the beginning of June. This month we already saw days with more than 2 million people.

The probability of reaching 2.3M TSA checkpoint travel numbers for three consecutive days, as one can see in the 2019 data, is a function of the overall travel numbers for a given period. Q1 2019 had similar levels than Q3 2021 (189M vs 173M). If we assume a normalization of travel numbers in 2021 (which is a tough assumption given the new Omnicron variant), there is a 2% probability that you'd get a 3 days in a row with 2.3M. This probability starts to move up accordingly. If we'd get a Q2 2019 volume in Q2 2022 this probability is very high, of 40%.
